Okay, it seems that you&#39;re not familiar with **front-end** JS and some other general concepts, so I&#39;ll give you an explanation about the basics and some references to help you understand the possible approaches, so you can decide what fits best your needs.

## 1. Fetching Data##
The simplest approach is to dynamically fetch data using [Fetch API][1], rendering it in your view and using further requests to communicate with your HTTP server to update with any changes you make.

Example:
&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    // Fetching data from some generic API
    fetch(&#39;https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users&#39;)
    .then( res =&gt; res.json() ) // Parses body into JSON
    .then( userList =&gt; {
      // Selecting our table element
      let table = document.querySelector(&#39;#t1 tbody&#39;);
      
      // For each user received, add his data on table
      userList.forEach( user =&gt; {
        let rowElement = document.createElement(&#39;tr&#39;),
            idElement = document.createElement(&#39;td&#39;),
            nameElement = document.createElement(&#39;td&#39;)
            emailElement = document.createElement(&#39;td&#39;);
        
        idElement.innerText = user.id;
        nameElement.innerText = user.name;
        emailElement.innerText = user.email;
        
        rowElement.appendChild(idElement);
        rowElement.appendChild(nameElement);
        rowElement.appendChild(emailElement);
        
        table.appendChild(rowElement);
      });
    })

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;table id=&quot;t1&quot; border=&quot;1&quot;&gt;
      &lt;thead&gt;
        &lt;tr&gt;
          &lt;th&gt;ID&lt;/th&gt;
          &lt;th&gt;Name&lt;/th&gt;
          &lt;th&gt;Email&lt;/th&gt;
        &lt;/tr&gt;
      &lt;/thead&gt;
      &lt;tbody&gt;
      &lt;/tbody&gt;
    &lt;/table&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Updating information is a little bit more simple, I recommend you to take a look in Fetch API link above, they have examples about doing HTTP requests to send data through POST method.

*Obs&#185;: If compatibility is important, take a look in [AJAX][2] to achieve similar things, but with more effort*

*Obs&#178;: You should consider learning a front-end JavaScript framework or using a library to make DOM manipulation (inserting/removing/updating/accessing HTML elements) easier.*

## 2. WebSockets ##
Totally a overkill, you surely don&#39;t need it (since you&#39;re building an API and this would require implementing an Web Socket server) but [here][3] it is, anyway.

## 3. Rendering a Template View##
This approach consists in using, at your HTTP server, some **template engine** to render before you serve your HTML (or any template engine format, like [Pug][4]), but after pulling data from your database.

[Here some example using Node.js + Express and Pug][5]

*Obs&#185;: You could do this &quot;manually&quot; without using template engines, but it would greatly increase the amount of work to achieve it.*

*Obs&#178;: Normally, in APIs this is not necessary, since the responsability of view rendering is somewhere else.*


